INSERT INTO public.exercises (id, name, des, level, image, metadata, topic, "contestId", "conceptId", "challengeId", status, "createdAt", "createdBy", "updatedAt", "updatedBy") VALUES ('0942378b-bcd5-423d-8a5b-0769f81e0a2a', ' autoCorrect', 'Hey, let''s do one more text editor themed challenge!
Autocorrect is a feature commonly found in mobile phones - when the user does a typo, it gets automatically replaced with the closest matching word from a list of known words.
Given a set of known words,Â `trainingWords`, and a sequence of words input by the user,Â `typedWords`, our task is to find the string we''ll get once the elements ofÂ typedWordsÂ have been autocorrected. Since parsing words can be tedious, bothÂ `trainingWords`Â andÂ `typedWords`Â are given as arrays of strings. The final text should be output as a single string (words joined by spaces).
How to select the closest word?\
To compare strings, we''ll be usingÂ Levenshtein distance, which is basically a measure of how manyÂ editsÂ would be required in order to transform one word into another. AnÂ editÂ is one of the following three operations:
-   insertionÂ - add a new character to some part of the string\
    (eg: fromÂ `"awkward"`Â toÂ `"bawkward"`)
-   deletionÂ - remove a character from some part of the string\
    (eg: fromÂ `"friend"`Â toÂ `"fiend"`)
-   replacementÂ - replace one character in the string with a different character\
    (eg: fromÂ `"nice"`Â toÂ `"vice"`)
For any string inÂ typedWordsÂ that doesn''t occur inÂ trainingWords, we''ll replace it with the string fromÂ trainingWordsÂ that''s considered closest according to Levenshtein distance. If there''s a tie for the closest match, choose the one that appears earliest inÂ trainingWords. Comparisons are case-sensitive.
Example
-   ForÂ `trainingWords = ["without", "night", "text", "cellar", "requirement", "some", "park", "instinct", "flourish", "computing", "vision", "mean", "round", "mistakes", "vain", "exemption", "fast"]`Â and t`ypedWords = ["some", "tex", "whith", "mistakesd"]`Â the output should be autocorrect(trainingWords, typedWords) =Â `"some text without mistakes"`
Input/Output
-   [execution time limit]Â 0.5 secondsÂ 
-   [input]Â array.string trainingWords
    The set of words our autocorrect algorithm has been trained on. All of the words in the output will be chosen from this list. All words consist of uppercase and lowercase letters only. There are no repeat words in the list.
    *Guaranteed constraints:\
    *1 â‰¤ trainingWords.length â‰¤ 2000\
